title: 🇧🇬 Bulgaria: Five Delegations Film Eurovision Backup Performances in Sofia
text:
🇧🇬 Bulgaria: Five Delegations Film Eurovision Backup Performances in Sofia
The delegations of Bulgaria, Cyprus, Greece, Malta and Moldova have all filmed their back-up performances for Eurovision 2021 in Sofia, Bulgaria.
Bulgaria along with Malta, Greece, Moldova, and Cyprus have all traveled to Sofia to film their back-up performances, with Cyprus and Greece having completed filming. The recording of backup (Live on tape) performances in Bulgaria has been produced by the same company that worked with BNT to produce the Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2015 in Bulgaria. The performances are said to resemble the upcoming Eurovision stage performances as much as is technically possible. The filming took place in a studio in Sofia.
“It was a tough year for all of us being unable to work together, so I am extremely happy to be able to meet other talented performers on the Bulgarian soil. I am sure that we are going to have great time together here in Sofia.“ – VICTORIA
With most pre-party Eurovision events canceled in 2021, the filming of backup performances will likely be the only times the 2021 acts can meet in person in the lead-up to Eurovision 2021.
“Eurovision is all about giving opportunities for creative projects and exchange of knowledge. Bulgaria is already an important hub for cinematic and musical projects, among others. Now we are committed to becoming better in the production of live television programs, and hosting such projects is part of the journey to make Bulgaria an important destination for large-scale live television events. We are grateful to our partners from Ten Dots Virtual Production Studio and Marvin Dietmann’s amazing team for working together to make this possible and of course, to the delegations of Malta, Cyprus, Moldova and Greece for trusting in us.” – Genoveva Christova
Marvin Dietmann has been working with most of the acts in attendance to stage their live on tape recordings. Marvin Dittmann has already been revealed as the artistic director for Cyprus, Croatia, Bulgaria, Czech Republic, Spain, and Austria. It is still not clear how much Marvin Dietmann will be working with the delegations of Malta, Greece, and Moldova this week.
Bulgaria is not the only one to host multiple Delegations, Lithuania has also hosted a number of delegations earlier this month to film their backup performance. North Macedonia also filmed their backup performance alongside Serbia’s Hurricane in Belgrade. While some delegations such as Sweden or Norway have used their national selection stages for their backup performance.
To date the following countries have publicly confirmed that their backup performance has been filmed:
This year all 40 acts will need to film a backup performance as part of the many contingency measures the EBU has put in place to ensure the song contest can happen in May no matter what.
Each act can rehearse for as long as they wish for their backup tape performance. However, only three attempts over the course of one hour are given for the filming of the performance which is monitored by the EBU. The participating country can choose which is the three performances is to be used.
Video recordings from all cameras, as well as all audio recordings from mics, are sent immediately to the EBU so that they cannot be tampered with. Each act is filmed as if this was a live show, meaning the performance is one continuous take. The EBU has explained that the backup performance does not need to resemble the live performance in May. All backup performances must be filmed by the 25th of March.
Source: Eurovision Bulgaria | Image Source: BNT
Bulgaria in the Eurovision Song Contest At the 2017 Eurovision Song Contest, 17-year-old Kristian Kostov finished in second place in the Grand Final, bringing Bulgaria their best ever result. 2017 saw Bulgaria make only their third final in their Eurovision history, the first being in 2007 when Elitsa & Stoyan finished 5th with the song “Water”. Bulgaria debuted in the Eurovision Song Contest in Kyiv, Ukraine in 2005. The country competed annually from 2005 to 2013, before withdrawing for two years due to financial issues.
